Description:
The best I can describe it is that it‚Äôs like living a dream that is instantaneously revealed to actually have been a nightmare the whole time. The race doesn‚Äôt start until you blow up and have to figure it out.

-

Five weeks ago I overheard that the NYC marathon fell on Nov 3 - my 30th birthday - and I decided I was going to run it. I didn‚Äôt have a bib or a charity lined up but had faith I‚Äôd find one so started ‚Äútraining.‚Äù Three 45 mile weeks later with a 20 mile long run included and I had a bib. Talk about coming in fresh. 

At first the goal was just to break 3, then 2:45, then 2:40 and maybe run 2:30. Spoiler - I ran 2:38.

I‚Äôm not sure if I quite understand the marathon. It‚Äôs just a really long run that ends in more pain than a race. 

I kept waiting for the wall to hit me at 18-20 and when it never did I put the hammer down only to be duped. At mile 22.5 the real race started. 

Yes, aerobically and anaerobically I never felt challenged but my legs weren‚Äôt calloused enough after months off and a total build up of 5 weeks to hold off the most tenacious hamstring cramps I could imagine. The only thing I could do was run slow enough they wouldn‚Äôt cramp up. With 1200m to go, 99.99% of the way there, they seized so badly I almost came to a complete halt. I could basically see the finish line and my body said nah but somehow I made it there.

Activity Name: Gorges de la Caran√ßa pour le Day Off
Description: This hike was craaaazy!! Every 1km it was a totally different experience. Cliffs, and valleys and rivers oh my! So so cool. Also kind of (really) hard! This hike took 3.5hours - not 2, don‚Äôt know what Strava is on!!

Prob went too fast again on the last few - legs felt heavy still but better than this morning! Breathing/HR was fine (barely went over 190) just did one lactate test at rep 8 to help inform whether or not to do 12 (still learning what ‚Äúactual‚Äù threshold feels like in the legs and breathing so if I go just off of feel I could easily do too much?) lactate was above 4 still, so we called it at 10. Early days and need to make sure we don‚Äôt put me in a hole too early!

Honeymoon period is OVER!! lol def super fricken tired today!! (Don‚Äôt know if my PM double yesterday was too hilly? And that‚Äôs why I‚Äôm not recovered? It‚Äôs also week 2 lol) but legs felt like logs. Interestingly, the HR didn‚Äôt climb too much, but lactate readings were over 4 nmol/L immediately and unfortunately I couldn‚Äôt lower it even when we cut the reps (initially supposed to be 2k reps.) Which is interesting, definitely not a 1 to 1 correlation from HR to lactic it seems. This kind of makes sense with the sensation I was feeling -‚Äúheavy legs but breathing is fine‚Äù which I never really actually understood until today. (Usually I‚Äôm like what do you mean? They both feel bad??? lol.)

We won‚Äôt do as much lactate testing going forward, but it has been helpful in the early stages for calibrating my effort and feel for this type of work.
The baby ones were so cute!! Had to walk bits because they were a bit too close for comfort üòÖ This city girl doesn‚Äôt know what to do in a herd!

This went well! Again seem to be adapting really well to altitude/all this threshold. Felt strong so kept trying to push the splits- probably started to leave threshold on the last few. started going out too quick for the first 200 so have to practice using control and running them more even!

This is my third double threshold session @ altitude and I think my body likes both threshold and altitude! 1km repeats paces are approaching what I was doing at sea level at the same HR really quickly.

Goal for this base season is to be very disciplined about not overrunning threshold. I used to never pay attention to HR given mine is so high (eg in this session, my HR hit the 190s at points but I‚Äôm still under 3.0nmol/L when testing for lactate.) so I now know I just need to know my own range.
